What are Rare Gases?
Rare gases, also known as noble gases, are a group of chemically inert gases that include helium (He), neon (Ne), argon (Ar), krypton (Kr), xenon (Xe), and radon (Rn). These gases are critical in semiconductor manufacturing processes due to their unique properties, such as high thermal conductivity, low reactivity, and ability to create stable plasmas. They are widely used in applications like wafer production, LED manufacturing, epitaxy, and various etching and deposition processes essential for advanced chip fabrication.

The semiconductor industry relies on these gases for their exceptional purity and stability under extreme conditions. For instance, xenon is indispensable for extreme ultraviolet (EUV) lithography systems, while argon and krypton play vital roles in creating precise plasma environments for etching and deposition. Their inert nature prevents unwanted chemical reactions during manufacturing, ensuring higher yields and superior chip performance.

